solutions.content:
To get all the subsets, for each element in the array, we have 2 choices 
Either include it in subset or not.
Just need to improve on that approach to **remove duplicates**, which can be done easily by just making sure that if the last element in our present subset is equal to our present element, then you have to surely include present element in the subset , i.e, dont skip the present element.
The subset which will form if we don't include the present element will lead to duplicacy.
Basically :
```
if nums[posn] = subset.back() //  subset.back() = last element in our present subset
		next recursion call after including nums[posn] in the subset
else 	
		1. recursion call without including present element
		2. recursion call after including present element

```
###  C++ code 
```
class Solution {
    // Final 2d array/vector to hold the answer
    vector<vector<int>> ans;
public:
    void fun(vector<int> nums,int n,vector<int> v,int i=0)
    {
        // when posn reaches the end of the input array, insert the present vector in to ans.     
        if(i==n){
            ans.push_back(v);
            return;
        }
        /* when present element is not equal to last element in vector,
        then only skip the                  
        present element */    
        if(v.empty()||v.back()!=nums[i])
        {
            fun(nums,n,v,i+1);
        }
        /* add the present element to the present subset and call for the remaining array */
        v.push_back(nums[i]);
        fun(nums,n,v,i+1);
    }
    vector<vector<int>> subsetsWithDup(vector<int>& nums) {
        vector<int> v;
        // Sort the input array so that all duplicate elements are together.
        sort(nums.begin(),nums.end());

        fun(nums,nums.size(),v);

        return ans;
    }
};
```
