solutions.content:
This is a typical DFS solution, except we say that if we're at a number with a repeating value, the left subtree will not choose an edge corresponding with the repeated value.

So general structure:
At each step, recurse left excluding the duplicate number.
Then (unless this subtree is ignoring this value) recurse right with no limits.

Here's an example of how the execution for nums = [1, 2, 2] would go.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/40155b43-c4c7-4ef2-b1ed-80431f7102d4_1629418968.448155.png)

```
class Solution {
    public List<List<Integer>> subsetsWithDup(int[] nums) {
        return generateSubsets(nums, new ArrayList<List<Integer>>());
    }

    private ArrayList<List<Integer>> generateSubsets(int[] nums, ArrayList<List<Integer>> output){
        Arrays.sort(nums);
        generateSubsetsHelper(nums, 0, new ArrayList<Integer>(), output, false);

        return output;
    }

    private void generateSubsetsHelper(int[] nums, int depth, List<Integer> currentSequence, ArrayList<List<Integer>> output, boolean ignoreValue){
        if(depth == nums.length){
            // Add a finished sequence to the result
            output.add(new ArrayList<Integer>(currentSequence));
            return;
        }

        // If the next two numbers are repeating, then our left subtree will ignore it.
        boolean ignoreNext =  depth < nums.length - 1 && nums[depth] == nums[depth + 1];
        generateSubsetsHelper(nums, depth + 1, currentSequence, output, ignoreNext);

        if(!ignoreValue) {
            // Include current num
            currentSequence.add(nums[depth]);
            generateSubsetsHelper(nums, depth + 1, currentSequence, output, false);

            // Clean up before backtracking
            currentSequence.remove(currentSequence.size() - 1);
        }

    }
}
```

