The following solution approaches the problem using bit shifting and divide and conquer. It divides the problem using `start` and `end` pointers, and uses those values to shift the input and account for the base case.

```java
public class Solution {
    // you need treat n as an unsigned value
    public int reverseBits(int n) {
        return reverse(n, 0, 31);
    }

    private int reverse(int n, int start, int end) {
        if (start == end) {            
            return (n >>> (31-start)) % 2;
        }

        int mid = (end-start)/2+start;

        int left = reverse(n, start, mid);
        int right = reverse(n, mid+1, end);

        return (right << (end-mid)) + left;
    }
}
```

Basically, it keeps dividing the problem by half, until it reaches the base case where the subproblem is of size 1. In the base case, it returns the bit at the current position.

In a non-base case, it gets the reversed bits in the left and right subproblems, and uses bit shifting to concatenate the right subsolution and the left subsolution.

