solutions.content:
* **Solution**
A 32 bits unsigned integer will have 32 bits with index from 0 to 31 from right to left. So to inverse 32 bits unsigned integer we will go through all the bits of n from 0 to 31 and add the the bit to our result. In order to do that we must know some knowledge about binary number :
n << 1 = n shift left 1 = move all the bits of n value to the left by 1 unit
example: 0001 << 1 = 0010
n >> 1 = n shift right 1 = move all the bits of n value to right by 1 unit
example: 1000 >> 1 = 0100
Therefore to solve this problem we get the rightmost bit ( by doing n mod 2 because we're calculating in base 2 ) then add it to **result << 1**. To make sure the next bit is the rightmost bit we do **n>>1**, keep doing until we go through all 32 bits of n.


* **Time Complexity**
We use a constant loop so the time complexity is O(32) which means **O(1)**.

* **Space Complexity**
Because we use constant number of variables so the space complexity is **O(1)**.

* **Source Code**
