We could `split()` the `str` to get an array of words, but in extreme case when `str` is significantly longer than `pattern`, this is not as efficient. 
Below is a one pass two(three?) pointer solution that compares the pattern to word only when a space is reached. 

```java
class Solution {
    public boolean wordPattern(String pattern, String str) {
        String[] map = new String[26];
        Set<String> set = new HashSet<>();

        int i = 0, j = 0, start = 0;
        while (i < pattern.length() && j <= str.length()) {
            if (j == str.length() || str.charAt(j) == ' ') {
                String cur = str.substring(start, j);
                char c = pattern.charAt(i);
                if (map[c - 'a'] == null) {
                    map[c - 'a'] = cur;
                    if (!set.add(cur)) return false;
                }
                if (!map[c - 'a'].equals(cur)) return false;
                start = j + 1;
                i++;
            }
            j++;
        }

        return i == pattern.length() && j == str.length() + 1;
    }
}
```

